# **Model Card: Emotion Detection in Text**

---

## **Model Overview**

* **Developed by:** Avanish Kumar Singh
* **Version:** v1.0 (First Public Release)
* **Model Type:** TensorFlow/Keras Sequential Neural Network
  * Embedding layer (input\_dim=10,000; output\_dim=100)
  * Two stacked LSTM layers (128 units → 64 units; \`return\_sequences=True\` on the first LSTM)
  * Dropout layers (rate=0.5) after the second LSTM and first Dense layer
  * Dense hidden layer (64 units, activation="relu")
  * Final Dense output layer (6 units, activation="softmax")
* **Training Parameters:**
  * Optimizer: Adam (default learning rate)
  * Loss: Categorical cross-entropy
  * Batch size: 32
  * Epochs: 20
* **Vocabulary Size:** 10,000 tokens (+ \<OOV\> for rare words)
* **Max Sequence Length:** 50 tokens (truncated/padded)
* **Citation:** Notebook "Emotion\_LSTM in Colab"
* **License:** Open-source (MIT-style)
* **Contact:** [singhavanish8642@gmail.com](mailto:singhavanish8642@gmail.com)

---

## **Intended Use**

* **Primary Use:** Classify short social-media texts (tweets) into one of six emotion categories: sadness, anger, love, surprise, fear, or joy.
* **Intended Users:** NLP researchers, social scientists, developers for downstream applications.
* **Out-of-Scope:** Long documents, non-English text, fine-grained emotions, real-time streaming with heavy code-mixing.

---

## **Factors & Evaluation**

* **Relevant Factors:**
  * Text length distribution (2–50 tokens)
  * Vocabulary coverage (10,000 tokens \+ \<OOV\>)
  * Noise in social media text (cleaned via regex)
  * Mild class imbalance
* **Evaluation Factors:**
  * Emotion category performance
  * Sentiment polarity distribution (TextBlob)
  * (No demographic/user-level metadata available)

---

## **Metrics**

* **Overall:** Accuracy on the held-out test set (2,000 samples)
* **Per-Class:** Precision, Recall, F1-score, Support
* **Confusion Matrix:** 6x6 heatmap showing true vs. predicted labels
* **Decision Threshold:** Argmax over softmax probabilities
* **Handling Uncertainty:** No confidence intervals or cross-validation reported

---

## **Data**

* **Dataset:** [Publicly curated emotion Tweets dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/praveengovi/emotions-dataset-for-nlp)
  * Train: 16,000 samples (balanced)
  * Validation: 2,000 samples
  * Test: 2,000 samples
* **Source & Motivation:** Balanced representation of six basic emotions in social-media text.
* **Preprocessing:**
  * Text normalization: Lowercasing, URL/mention/hashtag removal, punctuation removal, lemmatization, stopword removal.
  * Tokenization: Limited to 10,000 tokens (+ \<OOV\>), sequences padded/truncated to 50 tokens.
* **Training Data:** Same corpus as Evaluation (16,000 train split)
* **Duplicates & Overlap:** One duplicate removed in the training set; no overlap between splits.

---

## **Ethical Considerations**

* **Dataset Biases:** Overrepresentation of specific groups, fewer "surprise" samples.
* **Privacy & Sensitive Content:** Data from public Twitter, residual personal context may remain.
* **Risk of Misuse:** Incorrect classification could mislead, not for mental-health diagnosis.
* **Mitigations:** No direct demographic bias analysis, recommend augmenting data with under-represented communities.
* **Transparency & Accountability:** Notebook code available, future audits recommended.

---

## **Caveats & Recommendations**

* **Generalization Limitations:** Trained on English tweets, performance may degrade on other languages/domains.
* **Class-Specific Weaknesses:** Lower F1-scores for "surprise" and "love."
* **Overfitting Signs:** Validation plateaus, suggest early stopping.
* **Evaluation Enhancements:** Disaggregate performance, k-fold cross-validation.
* **Next Steps:** Expand training data, add multilingual support, fairness analysis, explore alternative architectures.
